    <subsection xml:id="firstlook03-subsection-rc-circuits-revisited">
        <title>RC Circuits Revisited</title>

        <p>Now let us return to our RC circuit and consider different functions <m>E(t)</m> for the differential equation 
            <me>\frac{d E_C}{dt} = \frac{E(t) - E_C}{RC},</me>
        with <m>R = 1</m> and <m>C = 1</m>. First suppose that there is no voltage source in the circuit. If we let <m>E(t) = 0</m> for all <m>t \ge 0</m>, we will get the direction field of given in <xref ref="firstlook03-figure-no-current" />. The direction field agrees with our analytic solution
            <me>E_C(t) = v_0 e^{-t},</me>
        where <m>v_0 = E_C(0)</m>.</p>

        <figure xml:id="firstlook03-figure-no-current">

            <image width="60%" xml:id="firstlook03-no-current">
                <sageplot>
                    from sage.calculus.desolvers import desolve_rk4
                    t, y = var('t, y')
                    R = 1
                    C = 1
                    E(t) = 0
                    f(t, y) = (E(t) - y)/(R*C)
                    p = plot_slope_field(f, (t,0,10), (y,-10,10), headaxislength=3, headlength=3, axes_labels=['$t$','$E(t)$'])
                    p += desolve_rk4(f,y,ics=[0,1],ivar=t,output='plot',end_points=[0,10],thickness=2)
                    p += desolve_rk4(f,y,ics=[0,-1],ivar=t,output='plot',end_points=[0,10],thickness=2, color = "red")
                    p += desolve_rk4(f,y,ics=[0,10],ivar=t,output='plot',end_points=[0,10],thickness=2, color = "green")
                    p += desolve_rk4(f,y,ics=[0,-10],ivar=t,output='plot',end_points=[0,10],thickness=2, color = "cyan")
                    p
                </sageplot>
                <description>a direction field of slope arrows and three curves following the arrows with the curves approaching zero</description>
            </image>

            <caption>The direction field for no current</caption>

        </figure>

        <p>If we assume that we have a nonzero constant source of voltage, <m>E(t) = K</m>, in our circuit such as a battery, then we obtain the separable differential equation
            <me>\frac{d E_C}{dt} = K - E_C.</me>
        The direction field for this differential equation for <m>K = 10</m> is given in <xref ref="firstlook03-figure-constant-current" />.</p>

        <figure xml:id="firstlook03-figure-constant-current">

            <image width="60%" xml:id="firstlook03-constant-current">
                <description>a direction field of slope arrows and three curves following the arrows with the curves approaching two</description>
                <sageplot>
                    from sage.calculus.desolvers import desolve_rk4
                    t, y = var('t, y')
                    R = 1
                    C = 1
                    E(t) = 10
                    f(t, y) = (E(t) - 5*y)/(R*C)
                    p = plot_slope_field(f, (t,0,4), (y,-10,10), headaxislength=3, headlength=3, axes_labels=['$t$','$E(t)$'])
                    p += desolve_rk4(f,y,ics=[0,1],ivar=t,output='plot',end_points=[0,4],thickness=2)
                    p += desolve_rk4(f,y,ics=[0,-1],ivar=t,output='plot',end_points=[0,4],thickness=2, color = "red")
                    p += desolve_rk4(f,y,ics=[0,10],ivar=t,output='plot',end_points=[0,4],thickness=2, color = "green")
                    p += desolve_rk4(f,y,ics=[0,-10],ivar=t,output='plot',end_points=[0,4],thickness=2, color = "cyan")
                    p
                </sageplot>
            </image>

            <caption>The direction field for a constant current</caption>

        </figure>

       <p>If we attach a battery to our circuit at time <m>t = 0</m> and then disconnect the battery at <m>t = 4</m>, then we obtain a different solution. For example, if
            <me>E(t) =
            \begin{cases}
            10     &amp; 0 \leq t \leq 4, \\
            0     &amp; t \gt 4,
            \end{cases}</me>
        we will obtain a different direction field (<xref ref="firstlook03-figure-single-pulse" />).</p>

        <figure xml:id="firstlook03-figure-single-pulse">
            <description>a direction field of slope arrows and three curves following the arrows with the curves approaching ten and then to zero once the time is four</description>
            <image width="60%" xml:id="firstlook03-single-pulse-current">
                <sageplot>
                    from sage.calculus.desolvers import desolve_rk4
                    t, y = var('t, y')
                    R = 1
                    C = 1
                    E(t) = 10
                    f(t, y) = (E(t) - y)/(R*C)
                    p = plot_slope_field(f, (t,0,3.9), (y,0,20), headaxislength=2, headlength=2, axes_labels=['$t$','$E(t)$'])
                    p += desolve_rk4(f,y,ics=[0,0],ivar=t,output='plot',end_points=[0,4],thickness=2)
                    p += desolve_rk4(f,y,ics=[0,20],ivar=t,output='plot',end_points=[0,4],thickness=2, color = "red")
                    E(t) = 0
                    f(t, y) = (E(t) - y)/(R*C)
                    p += plot_slope_field(f, (t,4.1,8), (y,0,20), headaxislength=2, headlength=2, axes_labels=['$t$','$E(t)$'])
                    p += desolve_rk4(f,y,ics=[4,10],ivar=t,output='plot',end_points=[4,8],thickness=2)
                    p += desolve_rk4(f,y,ics=[4,10],ivar=t,output='plot',end_points=[4,8],thickness=2, color = "red")
                    p
                </sageplot>
            </image>
            <caption>The direction field for a single pulse</caption>
            
        </figure>

        <p>If our voltage source emits a series of pulses, say
            <me>E(t) =
            \begin{cases}
            10 &amp; 0 \leq t \lt 4, \\
            0 &amp; 4 \leq t \lt 8, \\
            10 &amp; 8 \leq t \lt 12, \\
            &amp; \vdots
            \end{cases}</me>
        then the direction field for our differential equation is given in <xref ref="firstlook03-figure-series-pulses" />.</p>

